<?xml version='1.0' encoding='utf-8'?>

<!-- ====================================================================== 
   El calentamiento es un <exploration> (distinto a las otras actividades)
   Para RRRRR usar el estilo del calentamiento. Por ejemplo, usar 
   RRRRRR=observa con los "Observa y Pregúntate"
===========================================================================  -->
<exploration xml:id="warm-observa-otraTablaInteresante" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude"> 

<title>Observa y pregúntate: Otra tabla interesante</title>

<statement>
  <p>¿Qué observas? ¿Qué te preguntas?</p>
  <tabular halign="center" valign="middle" top="medium" left="medium">
    <row bottom="medium">
      <cell right="medium"><alert>+</alert></cell>
      <cell right="medium"><alert>98</alert></cell>
      <cell right="medium"><alert>99</alert></cell>
      <cell right="medium"><alert>100</alert></cell>
      <cell right="medium"><alert>101</alert></cell>
      <cell right="medium"><alert>102</alert></cell>
    </row>
    <row left="medium">
      <cell right="medium" bottom="medium"><alert>98</alert></cell>
      <cell right="minor" bottom="minor"><nbsp/></cell>
      <cell right="minor" bottom="minor">197</cell>
      <cell right="minor" bottom="minor"><nbsp/></cell>
      <cell right="minor" bottom="minor">199</cell>
      <cell right="minor" bottom="minor"><nbsp/></cell>
    </row>
    <row left="medium">
      <cell right="medium" bottom="medium"><alert>99</alert></cell>
      <cell right="minor" bottom="minor">197</cell>
      <cell right="minor" bottom="minor"><nbsp/></cell>
      <cell right="minor" bottom="minor">199</cell>
      <cell right="minor" bottom="minor"><nbsp/></cell>
      <cell right="minor" bottom="minor">201</cell>
    </row>
    <row left="medium">
      <cell right="medium" bottom="medium"><alert>100</alert></cell>
      <cell right="minor" bottom="minor"><nbsp/></cell>
      <cell right="minor" bottom="minor">?</cell>
      <cell right="minor" bottom="minor"><nbsp/></cell>
      <cell right="minor" bottom="minor">?</cell>
      <cell right="minor" bottom="minor"><nbsp/></cell>
    </row>
    <row left="medium">
      <cell right="medium" bottom="medium"><alert>101</alert></cell>
      <cell right="minor" bottom="minor">199</cell>
      <cell right="minor" bottom="minor"><nbsp/></cell>
      <cell right="minor" bottom="minor">201</cell>
      <cell right="minor" bottom="minor"><nbsp/></cell>
      <cell right="minor" bottom="minor">203</cell>
    </row>
    <row left="medium">
      <cell right="medium" bottom="medium"><alert>102</alert></cell>
      <cell right="minor" bottom="minor"><nbsp/></cell>
      <cell right="minor" bottom="minor">201</cell>
      <cell right="minor" bottom="minor"><nbsp/></cell>
      <cell right="minor" bottom="minor">203</cell>
      <cell right="minor" bottom="minor"><nbsp/></cell>
    </row>
</tabular>
</statement>

<solution>
    <p>[+++++++++++++++]</p>
    <p>Students may notice:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>The same numbers are across the top and along the left side.</li>
      <li>Every other cell is filled.</li>
      <li>There are two question marks in the table.</li>
      <li>The sums go up by 2 from left to right, top to bottom, and diagonally from upper left to lower right.</li>
      <li>The sums that make a diagonal line from lower left to upper right are the same number.</li>
      <li>All the sums are odd numbers.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Students may wonder:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>What numbers go in the cells with a question mark?</li>
      <li>Why do the numbers in the table go up by 2 from left to right and top to bottom?</li>
      <li>Why are the sums odd numbers?</li>
      <li>Are there other patterns in the table?</li>
    </ul>
  </solution>


<!-- ============================================================== 
   Notas profesor <prelude> (se pueden mostrar previo al enunciado)                      
===================================================================  -->
<prelude component="profesor"> 

  <!-- Estándares CCSS asociados -->
  <paragraphs>
    <title><custom ref="ccss-actividad-titulo"/></title> 
    <ul>
      <li> 
        <custom ref="ccss-addressing"/>
        <xref ref="ccss-3-OA-D-9" text="custom">3.OA.D.9</xref>
      </li>   
    </ul>
  </paragraphs>

  <!-- Tiempo recomendado -->
  <paragraphs>
    <title><custom ref="recommended-time-titulo"/></title>
    <p>10 minutos</p>
  </paragraphs>

  <!-- Introducción de la actividad -->  
  <paragraphs>
    <title><custom ref="narrative-actividad-titulo"/></title>
    <p>[+++++++++++++++]</p>
    <p>The purpose of this warm-up is to elicit observations about patterns in sums of two- and three-digit addends in an addition table. The table is partially filled out to highlight some properties of operations. For example, the sums in the table can illustrate the commutative property (<m>99 + 98</m> and <m>98 + 99</m> both give 197). The numbers also prompt students to notice patterns in sums of odd and even numbers. For example, the sum of an odd number and an even one is always odd.</p>
    <p>While students may notice and wonder many things about the addition table, focus the discussion on the patterns in the table and possible explanations for them. When students make sense of patterns in sums and explain them in terms of the features of the addends and how they are added, they notice and use regularity in repeated reasoning (MP7).</p>
  </paragraphs>

  <!-- Launch -->
  <paragraphs>
    <title><custom ref="launch-titulo"/></title>
    <p>[+++++++++++++++]</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Groups of 2</li>
      <li>Display the table.</li>
      <li>
        <q>¿Qué observan? ¿Qué se preguntan?</q>
      </li>
      <li>1 minute: quiet think time</li>
    </ul>
  </paragraphs>

  <!-- Instrucciones para el desarrollo de la actividad -->
  <paragraphs>
    <title><custom ref="instructions-teacher-actividad-titulo"/></title>
    <p>[+++++++++++++++]</p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <q>Discutan con su pareja lo que pensaron</q>
      </li>
      <li>1 minute: partner discussion</li>
      <li>Share and record responses.</li>
    </ul>
  </paragraphs>

</prelude>


<!-- ============================================================== 
   Notas profesor <postlude> (se pueden mostrar después del enunciado)                      
===================================================================  -->
<postlude component="profesor">

  <!-- Síntesis de la actividad -->
  <paragraphs>
    <title><custom ref="synthesis-actividad-titulo"/></title>
    <p>[+++++++++++++++]</p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <q>¿Cómo creen que funciona la tabla?</q>  (The table shows addition. Each number in the row at the top is added to each number in the first column on the left.)
      </li>
      <li>
        <q>¿Qué números deberían ir en las celdas que tienen un signo de interrogación?</q>  (199 and 201.) 
        <q>¿Cómo lo saben?</q>
      </li>
      <li>For each of the following questions, give students a minute of quiet think time. Illustrate their responses with equations, if possible.</li>
      <li>
        <q>¿Por qué estas sumas aumentan de 2 en 2 de izquierda a derecha y de arriba a abajo?</q>  (Because of the skipping, one number being added goes up by 2, so the sum also goes up by 2.)
      </li>
      <li>
        <q>¿Por qué las sumas desde la esquina superior izquierda hasta la esquina inferior derecha aumentan de 2 en 2?</q>  (Each of the two numbers being added go up by 1, so the sum goes up by 2.)
      </li>
      <li>
        <q>¿Por qué las sumas que forman una línea desde la esquina inferior izquierda a la esquina superior derecha son el mismo número?</q>  (Each time, the first number being added goes up by 1 and the second number goes down by 1, so the sum stays the same.)
      </li>
      <li>Consider asking: 
        <q>¿Las sumas o los sumandos son pares o impares? ¿Qué observan?</q>  (In each pair of addends, one number is even and the other number is odd. All the sums are odd.)
      </li>
    </ul>
  </paragraphs>

</postlude>

</exploration>